S There is a heated debate whether schools and universities should replace printed materials by new technological inventions? There have been made lots of surveys among schools in order to show the balance between using of printed materials and technology such as computers and mobile phones. Those surveys have came out with surprising results. However, there are two sides of the coin. On one side, the first group included in the surveys were students. They prefer to use technology rather then books. The evidence is provided by their flexibility. For example, you can be on-line with your teacher when you are abesent from school. Not to mention, looking for information on the internet, or share information among other students. Morover, many printed materials do not need to be updated and that is why, they would be provided vie the internet. This solution does not seem to be such a big financial burden as buying new printed materials. On the other side, teachers claim that most of the books can not be replaced by technology. These materials need to be updated. Second reason for this is prices of implementing the new technology in schools which brings together another problems and take a long time to be fully effective. As far as I am concerned, we live in a new century in which the technology is playing the most important role in many fields of education. Another persuasive argument is that we can not avoid using of the new technology in our daily life. The technology is eases our life in most aspects you think about. Similarily, the basic education procedures will still remain for many years \u2013 in a roundabout kind of way.
