S There is no reasonable answer for the question of how long your life is supposed to be. The entire problem is unsolvable, due to the reason that nothing can controll the lenght of your life. Some people find their way through an accident and others suffer from a disease. However, you can decide how you spend the years you have and if you are rather risky or circumspect. Living until you are 100 years old, but missing quintessential opportunities, because you deem them as too hazardious, is a path most people would choose. You always would have something to hold on to and experience one whole century, in the case that your spouse begets children early they might even find their way to heaven before you do. Alternatively, the opportunity is given that you live shorter, but with more mindblowing situations. There is no doubt that living for the moment is intelligible, nevertheless your activities always would include the slight possibility that you might die. The danger of dying by everything you are doing, simply because you want to do the most out of it sounds rather unreasonable. Taking all these steps into consideration the shorter live is the one I would choose. The thread of dying is something we experience every day and missing momentos moments, simply because you want to turn 100 one day sounds unplausible for me. Furthermore, the mindset that you do your utmost to live as longs as possible does not feel like worth caring around as a burden with me, striktly speaking it would dismantle me.
