S In general office spaces are designed to match the room or the building bought or rented to work, they are generally not thought in advance. It results then that some working spaces are smaller than a closet some others tend to be too wide. In my opinion , the least effective between the two arragements is the first one: working in a tight space, sometimes with not even the natural daylight, risks to undermine firstly the employees' mood and secondly their health in general. For instance keeping in the same room, computers, printers and workers can render the whole space too hot and too noisy. Another aspect to consider, in separated offices, are the reduced exchanges amid colleagues, this might limit the leverage of the team building culture. I would say that this kind of office arrangements might be fine only if the secrecy is the priority in the working purposes. I would definitely prefer working in a wide and open space where interactions among coworkers are facilitated. The absence of walls is certainly a good choice in an office to foster a cooperative community as such, in an open space assistance, in case of problems, is easier and in addition information runs faster than in separated rooms so that everyone in office is informed about what it is going on. Open spaces help as well to create a friendlier working environment which enables workers to be at ease and contribute in a more positive manner to the firm objectives. In conclusion, although little spaces or separated spaces may respect the privacy of workers , in an open space, once more, I do believe that either the workers as well as the firm itself benefit of the arrangements in terms of results and wellbeing.
