S In this days we are witnessing heated debates about students volunteer work. Students in high schools had to make their commintments to undertake a certain amount of hours of volunteer work in order to graduate. To be more precise, they were given a chance to choose one from the school\u2019s offer. There were counted around 100 volunteer works positions available. However, many of them had to turn a blind eye on this requirement and saying it is not in accordance with school standards. There are two sides of the coin. On one side, it is obvious that in some countries we can find schools aimed at practical use. To give an illustration, plants growing and other manual works needed to be practiced. In fact, to receive a certificate of a qualification. As a final stage of your education you will be asked to undertake a test or an exam to show your gained knowledge in a certain level. On the other side, there are schools that are not aimed on education included manual or similar work. Those students are prepared for the high level of education or in the mangers or leaders positions within an organization. For example, financial sector or they even work in the field of education. If I look at both sides, I have to admit my disagreement with implementation of volunteer work in schools. Students should not be forced to earn money for their education. In my view, the responsibility to educate each generation of students is on the government. What I am trying to say is that parents of children would not pay for their education. Let me put it in other way, if we want to have a growing economy in the future, we have to invest and participate more on developing our pillar of education. Last but not least, If I had a chance to make a change, I would have given more money from the government budget to the education sector. Another key things to remember is reducing administrative and replacement old methods of learning by using new technology.
