S In my opinion,l think learning to speak a foreign lauguage is not as impotant these days as it was in the past. Now let me tell you why. In the early 1500s-1700s,the English got off to a late start with the whole colonizing thing. The want to expand their territory. They watched as Spain and Portugal quickly snapped up land in the Americas during the 1500s. And made a fortune on gold,silver,and sugar. Plus,English's long time Enemy,the French,were starting to explore the north. So the English wondered if they should start colonizing too. But There's a problem,if they want to colonizing,they had to know a lot about the places they're going to colonize. If they don't,they might fail to make some deals with the native people in the South. So the king authorized a public studying class to let the sailors know where are they going to,what their culture is,and how to communicate in their language. But the native American's didn't speak an easy language,so it takes months to know the basics of it. Back to the present,we don't need a lot of effort trying to know what someone's saying. We just take out our phones and download a translator. Easy-peasy.
